'''Brynjolv Baardson''' (December 25, 1921 – July 19, 2002)<ref>{{cite web|last=Baardson|first=Brynjolv|title=Brynjolv Baardson|url=http://www.genealogybank.com/gbnk/ssdi/doc/ssdi/v1:1130630A9CC17E49|publisher=genealogybank|accessdate=23 October 2013}}</ref> was a Norwegian sailor and businessperson, and a US Army officer.

During [[World War II]], Baardson was a sailor in the Norwegian merchant marine, serving aboard the [[MS Ravnaas (1931)|MS ''Ravnaas'']] when she was sunk by Japanese aircraft off [[Samar Island]] in December 1941. In January 1942 he volunteered to the United States Army, and fought with in the jungles of [[Cebu Island]], was imprisoned in Japanese [[prisoner-of-war]] camps in the Philippines and Japan along with American soldiers, and returned to the US in 1945, where he was given the rank of Captain.<ref name=warsailors>{{cite web|url=http://www.warsailors.com/singleships/ravnaas.html |title=M/S Ravnaas |publisher=Warsailors.com |year=2009 |accessdate=30 October 2011 }}</ref><ref>Taraldsen 1985: p. 243</ref> He published the memoir book ''Kiotskee!'' in 1981, with accounts of his experiences in the jungle of Cebu and later in Japanese internment camps.<ref>Baardson 1981</ref> His memoirs are extensively cited in [[Guri Hjeltnes]]' work from 1997 on the history of the Norwegian merchant fleet.<ref>Hjeltnes 1999: pp. 31&ndash;32, 258–261, 355–359, 395, 553, 566, 568–569, 583</ref>

He was married to Kirsten Margrethe Baardson (1929&ndash;1996), and is the father of theatre director [[Bentein Baardson]].<ref name=nbl-bentein-baardson>{{cite encyclopedia|year=|title=Bentein Baardson |encyclopedia=[[Norsk biografisk leksikon]]|first=Lise |last=Lyche |authorlink= |editor=[[Knut Helle|Helle, Knut]]|publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget|location=Oslo|url=http://www.snl.no/.nbl_biografi/Bentein_Baardson/utdypning|language=Norwegian|accessdate=30 October 2011}}</ref>

