'''Marius Jacques Kloppers''' (born 26 August 1962) is a South African-born Australian businessman and former [[CEO]] of [[BHP Billiton]], the world's largest mining company.<ref>[http://www.crikey.com.au/Business/20070531-Another-foreigner-climbs-the-mountain-at-BHP.html Crikey - Another foreigner climbs to the top of the heap at BHP-Billiton - Another foreigner climbs to the top of the heap at BHP-Billiton<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> He was also Executive Director and Chairman of the Group Management Committee from 2007 to 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=BHP Billiton web site|url=http://www.bhpbilliton.com/home/aboutus/leadership/Pages/default.aspx}}</ref> He was asked to retire as CEO on 1 October 2013, and was succeeded by [[Andrew Mackenzie (businessman)|Andrew Mackenzie]].<ref name=heraldsun>{{cite web |last=Russell |first=Christopher |title=BHP CEO Marius Kloppers steps down |url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/business/companies/bhp-ceo-marius-kloppers-to-retire/story-fndgp8b1-1226581630471 |publisher=[[Herald Sun]] |date=20 February 2013 |accessdate=20 February 2013}}</ref><ref name=bhpb>{{cite web |title=MARIUS KLOPPERS TO RETIRE, ANDREW MACKENZIE TO BECOME CEO |url=http://www.bhpbilliton.com/~/media/bhp/documents/investors/news/2013/130220_bhp-billiton-ceo-retirement-and-appointment.pdf?la=en |publisher=[[BHP Billiton]] |date=20 February 2013 |accessdate=20 February 2013}}</ref>

== Education ==
Kloppers graduated from [[Helpmekaar Kollege]], then a public school in Johannesburg (IEB currently). Kloppers graduated with a Bachelor of Chemical Engineering from the [[University of Pretoria]] and subsequently went on to receive a PhD at [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]]. He also graduated with an MBA from [[INSEAD]].

== Career ==
Kloppers worked in petrochemicals at [[Sasol]] and materials research with [[Mintek]] in South Africa. Following completion of his MBA at INSEAD, he then worked with management consultants [[McKinsey & Company|McKinsey & Co]] in Netherlands before joining Billiton in 1993. In 2007, at the age of 44, he was appointed CEO of the largest resource company in the world, BHP Billiton. He officially assumed the position of CEO on 1 October 2007. In 2009 his annual compensation was $US 10,399,589, of which $2M was salary and the balance was bonus.<ref>{{cite news |title=BHP chief gets $12 million paycheck, up 51pc |url=http://www.news.com.au/perthnow/story/0,21598,26075598-5005361,00.html |work=The Sunday Times (Australia) |publisher=The Sunday Times (Australia) |accessdate=2009-09-14 | date=2009-09-15}}</ref>

